There seem to be a few issues with the code you provided. Within the JavaScript block, you’re appending the shadowElement directly to the btn button element, which alters the button’s inner layout and may not yield the desired center alignment for the emoji shadow. Instead, you should create a container that can hold both the emoji button and its shadow, ensuring they don’t interfere with each other’s positioning.

Here’s how you can modify the button creation and append the shadowElement in a way that separates it from the button interaction:


emojiBtns.forEach(btn => {
// Create a container for both the button and its shadow.
const btnContainer = document.createElement(‘div’);
btnContainer.classList.add(‘emoji-btn-container’);
btnContainer.style.position = ‘relative’;

// Move the button’s content and attributes to the container.
btnContainer.innerHTML = btn.innerHTML;
btnContainer.className = btn.className;
btn.removeAttribute(‘class’);
btn.className = ‘emoji-btn’;

// Create the shadow span.
const shadowElement = document.createElement(‘span’);
shadowElement.classList.add(‘emoji-shadow’);
shadowElement.innerHTML = btn.innerHTML;

// Clear the button content and append the container and shadow to it.
btn.innerHTML = ‘’;
btn.appendChild(btnContainer);
btn.appendChild(shadowElement);

// The original button now serves as a wrapper for both elements.
btn.parentNode.insertBefore(btn, btn.nextSibling);
});



Make sure to adjust your CSS accordingly, and set your .emoji-btn to have the appropriate styles for the button, while .emoji-btn-container handles the emoji display. With these changes, the shadow won’t interfere with the button’s functionality, and you can position the shadow independently of the button.

